    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "okay that makes sense. but who actually holds the money? like is it just sitting in a regular bank account or something? i'm just nervous about any large sums of money just sitting around during the process.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "You are absolutely right to be concerned about where the money goes, and it is not just sitting in a regular, unsecured bank account. The escrow agent holds the funds in a specialized, segregated account that is legally distinct from their personal assets and often separate from other client funds to ensure the buyer's money is protected and clearly identifiable. This segregation is a strict legal requirement designed specifically to prevent commingling and ensure that the funds are only released to the seller once the deed is officially transferred.\n\nWhile the money does sit there for a period of time, it is not \"lost\" or idle in a risky way; it is actively being monitored by the escrow officer who ensures all title searches, inspections, and loan approvals are complete before the check is written. If you are worried about the security of the funds, you can ask your realtor to show you the escrow agreement or the bank's segregation policy, which will confirm that these funds are held in a highly regulated environment.",
